# Ironclad CLI Design System

All CLI output in Ironclad must follow these conventions. This applies to every file that writes to stdout or stderr with formatting: `main.rs`, `cli.rs`, and any future CLI modules.

## Theme Variants

Three selectable palettes via `--theme` flag (default: `crt-green`). Set via `IRONCLAD_THEME` env var or `--theme=<name>`.

| Variant      | Flag value    | Aesthetic |
|--------------|---------------|-----------|
| CRT Green    | `crt-green`   | Phosphor green CRT monitor. Body text tinted green. |
| CRT Orange   | `crt-orange`  | Amber CRT monitor. Body text tinted warm orange. |
| Terminal     | `terminal`    | No foreground tint. Uses the terminal's native colors. |

## Color Palette

Two text levels + standard semantics per variant. Use the `Theme` struct from `ironclad_core::style` -- never raw ANSI codes.

**Text should never be gray.** Each variant has two text levels (accent and body) plus shared semantic colors:

| Semantic Name | CRT Green          | CRT Orange         | Terminal           | Usage |
|---------------|--------------------|--------------------|--------------------| ------|
| `accent`      | 256-color 46       | 256-color 208      | bold (no fg)       | Emphasis, headings, highlighted values. |
| `dim`         | 256-color 40       | 256-color 172      | (empty)            | Body text. Step counters, metadata, secondary text. |
| `mono`        | 256-color 46       | 256-color 208      | bold (no fg)       | Monospace values: IDs, paths, code. |
| `reset`       | clear + tint 40    | clear + tint 172   | plain `\x1b[0m`    | After every styled span. CRT variants re-tint; Terminal does not. |

Shared semantic colors (same across all variants):

| Name      | Code       | Usage |
|-----------|------------|-------|
| `success` | `\x1b[92m` | "All passed" summaries. |
| `warn`    | `\x1b[93m` | Warning labels. |
| `error`   | `\x1b[91m` | Error labels. |
| `info`    | `\x1b[96m` | Debug info, provider names. |

Use **accent for emphasis** and **reset for body text**, side by side.

**Typography modifiers** (combine with colors):

| Modifier | Code         | Usage |
|----------|--------------|-------|
| `bold`   | `\x1b[1m`   | Section titles, command names, emphasis. Never use for body text. |
| `hard_reset` | `\x1b[0m` | Full terminal reset. Used only at program exit. |

## Icon System

Icons are accessed via `theme().icon_ok()`, `theme().icon_action()`, etc. -- never hardcoded emoji literals. In default mode they render as emojis with inherent color; in nerdmode they render as ASCII bracket sequences.

| Accessor         | Emoji | ASCII (nerdmode) | Meaning |
|------------------|-------|------------------|---------|
| `icon_ok()`      | ✅    | `[OK]`           | Exists, loaded, accessible, PASS, done. |
| `icon_action()`  | ⚡    | `[>>]`           | Created, fixed, installed, ready, power on. |
| `icon_warn()`    | ⚠️    | `[!!]`           | Warning, missing, caution, WARN, SKIP. |
| `icon_detail()`  | ▸     | `>`              | Indented detail lines beneath a step. No color. |
| `icon_error()`   | ⛓     | `[XX]`           | Error, failure, FAIL. |
| Section divider  | ───   | ───              | Horizontal rule between major sections. (Box-drawing, unchanged in nerdmode.) |

In `cli.rs`, destructure via `let (OK, ACTION, WARN, DETAIL, ERR) = icons();` alongside the `colors()` tuple. In `main.rs`, call `t.icon_ok()` etc. directly on the theme reference.

## Layout Conventions

### Step Format (boot sequence, check output)
```
  ✅ [01/12] Database initialized
       ▸ path: ~/.ironclad/state.db
       ▸ mode: WAL (persistent)
```
- 2-space indent before emoji
- Step counter in body text (dim)
- Message in bold
- Details indented 7 spaces with ▸ pointer (inherits body text)

### Section Headers
```
  ── Sessions ──────────────────────
```
- 2-space indent, box-drawing rules, title in bold

### Status Lines
```
  ⚡ Ready in 142ms
  ✅ Setup complete! Run ironclad serve to start.
```
- ⚡ for power-on / startup moments
- ✅ for completion / done confirmations

### Error Output
```
  ⚠️ Configuration validation failed: missing [models] section
```
- 2-space indent + warning emoji

### Table Output
- Use the existing `print_table_row` / `print_table_header` pattern
- Column widths calculated from content
- Headers in body text, data rows in body text
- Accent for key values requiring emphasis

## Banner Rules

The Roboticus ASCII banner (`print_banner()`) displays on:
- `ironclad serve` (server startup)
- `ironclad init` (first-time setup)

Suppress the banner on all single-shot commands (status, config, check, mechanic, etc.). These should be fast and quiet.

## Color Control

### NO_COLOR Standard
Respect the `NO_COLOR` environment variable (no-color.org). When set to any non-empty value, suppress all ANSI color and style codes. Symbols and text must still be readable.

### TTY Detection
When stderr is not a terminal (piped or redirected), default to no color. This prevents ANSI codes from polluting log files and pipe chains.

### --color Flag
Global CLI flag: `--color=auto|always|never`
- `auto` (default): color if TTY, no color if piped, respect `NO_COLOR`
- `always`: force color regardless of TTY or `NO_COLOR`
- `never`: no color

Precedence: `--color` flag > `NO_COLOR` env var > TTY auto-detection.

### --theme Flag
Global CLI flag: `--theme=crt-green|crt-orange|terminal`
- `crt-green` (default): phosphor green CRT aesthetic
- `crt-orange`: amber CRT aesthetic
- `terminal`: no foreground override, uses terminal's native colors

Also settable via `IRONCLAD_THEME` env var.

### --nerdmode Flag
Global CLI flag: `--nerdmode` (also `IRONCLAD_NERDMODE=1` env var).

A composite retro mode that activates three behaviors simultaneously:

1. **CRT tint override** -- Forces CRT Green palette. If `--theme=crt-orange` was explicitly set, orange is preserved. Only `terminal` gets overridden to green.
2. **ASCII icons** -- All emojis are replaced with ASCII bracket sequences at render time.
3. **Typewriter draw forced on** -- Overrides `--no-draw`; text always renders character-by-character.

Effectively: `--nerdmode` = CRT green (unless orange) + ASCII symbols + typewriter on.

#### ASCII Symbol Mapping (nerdmode)

| Normal Emoji | ASCII    | Meaning |
|-------------|----------|---------|
| ✅           | `[OK]`   | Status pass, exists, done |
| ⚡           | `[>>]`   | Action, created, ready |
| ⚠️           | `[!!]`   | Warning, caution |
| ▸            | `>`      | Detail pointer |
| ⛓            | `[XX]`   | Error, failure |

#### Flag Interaction

| Flags combined               | Result |
|------------------------------|--------|
| `--nerdmode`                  | CRT Green + ASCII + draw ON |
| `--nerdmode --theme=crt-orange` | CRT Orange + ASCII + draw ON |
| `--nerdmode --theme=terminal` | CRT Green + ASCII + draw ON (terminal overridden) |
| `--nerdmode --no-draw`        | CRT Green + ASCII + draw ON (--no-draw overridden) |
| `--nerdmode --color=never`    | No color + ASCII + draw OFF (color=never wins) |

### Implementation
Use `ironclad_core::style::Theme`:
```rust
let theme = Theme::detect(); // defaults: NO_COLOR check, TTY, CrtGreen
// or
let theme = Theme::from_flags("auto", "crt-green"); // from --color and --theme flags
```

All output functions accept `&Theme` or use a thread-local/global theme. Never call `\x1b[...` directly.

## Accessibility

- **Emojis carry meaning and color**: ✅ ⚡ ⚠️ are distinguishable without ANSI codes. Color is inherent.
- **Nerdmode ASCII fallback**: `--nerdmode` replaces emojis with ASCII bracket sequences (`[OK]`, `[>>]`, `[!!]`, `>`, `[XX]`) for terminals that don't render emoji well or for the retro aesthetic.
- **Text is never gray**: only bright accent and body text. Two levels per variant, no murky mid-tones.
- **CRT typewriter draw**: text renders character-by-character. Disable with `--no-draw` (nerdmode overrides this).
- **Text alternatives**: status is always conveyed in text alongside icons (e.g., `✅ PASS` not just `✅`).
- **Graceful degradation**: when color is disabled, icons still carry meaning. Output remains structured.
- **Screen readers**: avoid box-drawing for critical information. Use it only for decoration.

## Future TUI Considerations

Ratatui is not used today. The CLI is for bootstrapping and maintenance. The web dashboard serves rich UI needs.

**When ratatui would be appropriate:**
- An `ironclad chat` command with streaming responses, message history, and markdown rendering
- A terminal dashboard with live-updating panels (as an alternative to the web dashboard)

**Design constraints to maintain TUI compatibility:**
- Keep business logic separate from output formatting
- The `Theme` color palette maps directly to ratatui's `Style` system
- Layout constants (indentation, widths) should be centralized, not hardcoded in format strings
- Command handlers should return structured data, not write directly to stdout -- this enables both CLI text rendering and future TUI widget rendering from the same data

## Command Hierarchy

### Design Principles

1. **Standard names, themed descriptions.** Command names follow established CLI conventions (`serve`, `status`, `config`). Thematic personality lives in help text and doc strings, not in command names.
2. **Subcommands for resources, flat for actions.** Any command that operates on a resource with multiple operations uses a subcommand enum (`memory list`, `memory search`). Single-action commands stay flat (`version`, `status`).
3. **Aliases preserve backward compatibility.** Renamed commands keep their old name as an alias (`cron` -> `schedule`, `onboard` -> `setup`, `breaker` -> `circuit`). Common alternatives are also aliased (`serve` accepts `start` and `run`, `mechanic` accepts `doctor`).
4. **No-arg shows help.** Running `ironclad` with no subcommand prints the help page instead of implicitly starting the server. Explicit is better than implicit.

### Command Categories

Commands are organized into five logical groups. The order in the `Commands` enum determines help output order.

| Category      | Commands |
|---------------|----------|
| Lifecycle     | `serve`, `init`, `setup`, `check`, `version`, `update` |
| Operations    | `status`, `mechanic`, `logs`, `circuit` |
| Data          | `sessions`, `memory`, `skills`, `schedule`, `metrics`, `wallet` |
| Configuration | `config`, `models`, `plugins`, `agents`, `channels`, `security` |
| System        | `daemon`, `web`, `reset`, `uninstall`, `completion` |

### Naming Rules

- **Nouns for resources** (`sessions`, `memory`, `wallet`, `plugins`) -- these take subcommands.
- **Verbs for actions** (`serve`, `check`, `reset`, `update`) -- these are flat.
- **No jargon** -- prefer `schedule` over `cron`, `circuit` over `breaker`.
- **Mechanical/robot tone in descriptions** -- "Boot the Ironclad runtime" not "Start the server"; "Run diagnostics and self-repair" not "Run health checks"; "Report firmware version" not "Print version info".

### Subcommand Consistency

Every resource command must follow the pattern:

```rust
#[command(subcommand)]
ResourceName(ResourceNameCmd),
```

With a corresponding enum:

```rust
#[derive(Subcommand)]
enum ResourceNameCmd {
    List,      // always present
    Show { id: String },
    // ... additional operations
}
```

### Global Flags

All global flags are defined on the `Cli` struct and propagated via `#[arg(global = true)]`:

| Flag | Short | Env Var | Purpose |
|------|-------|---------|---------|
| `--url` | | `IRONCLAD_URL` | Gateway URL for management commands |
| `--profile` | | `IRONCLAD_PROFILE` | Profile name for state isolation |
| `--config` | `-c` | `IRONCLAD_CONFIG` | Path to configuration file |
| `--color` | | | Color output: auto, always, never |
| `--theme` | | `IRONCLAD_THEME` | Color theme: crt-green, crt-orange, terminal |
| `--no-draw` | | | Disable CRT typewriter draw effect |
| `--nerdmode` | | `IRONCLAD_NERDMODE` | Composite retro mode |
| `--quiet` | `-q` | | Suppress informational output |
| `--json` | | | Output structured JSON |

### Function Naming in cli.rs

CLI handler functions follow the pattern `cmd_<command>_<subcommand>`:
- `cmd_status` -- flat command
- `cmd_sessions_list` -- subcommand
- `cmd_circuit_status` -- renamed subcommand
- `cmd_schedule_list` -- renamed + promoted subcommand

When a command is renamed, the function name must match the new name (`cmd_schedule_list`, not `cmd_cron_list`).

## Code Organization

All color and style logic lives in `ironclad_core::style`:
- `ThemeVariant` enum (`CrtGreen`, `CrtOrange`, `Terminal`) for palette selection
- `Theme` struct with semantic accessors (`theme.accent()`, `theme.error()`, etc.)
- `Theme::detect()` for automatic color mode detection (defaults to CrtGreen)
- `Theme::from_flags(color, theme)` for explicit `--color` and `--theme` flag handling
- `Theme::with_nerdmode(true)` for nerdmode composite behavior (ASCII icons, forced draw, variant override)
- `Theme::plain()` for no-color output
- Icon accessors: `icon_ok()`, `icon_action()`, `icon_warn()`, `icon_detail()`, `icon_error()` -- return emoji or ASCII depending on nerdmode

No other file should contain raw ANSI escape codes or hardcoded emoji literals.
